---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site';

const projects = (await getCollection('research')).sort(
  (a, b) => (a.data.order ?? 100) - (b.data.order ?? 100),
);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Research"
  description="I combine stochastic models with single-cell and spatial transcriptomics to make transfers across molecular, cellular, and tissue scales more explicit in infectious disease."
>
  <div class="page-wrap fade-trail">
    <header class="prose">
      <h1>Research</h1>
      <p>
        Host–pathogen outcomes depend on relationships that are hard to measure in one place:
        molecular fluctuations within cells, rare cellular states in a population, and spatial
        organization in tissue. Each scale is accessible experimentally, but the transfer among
        them is usually inferred rather than observed. I combine stochastic models with single-cell
        and spatial transcriptomics to make those transfers more explicit in infectious disease.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2 class="section-label">Projects</h2>
      <ul class="project-list">
        {
          projects.map((p) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`/research/${p.id}/`}>{p.data.title}</a>
              {p.data.excerpt && <p class="excerpt">{p.data.excerpt}</p>}
              {p.data.status && <p class="meta">{p.data.status}</p>}
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="prose research-overview">
      <h2>Current focus</h2>
      <h3>Spatial and single-cell transcriptomics in infectious disease</h3>
      <p>
        Tissue pathology and cellular molecular states describe related aspects of infection, but
        they are usually measured on different platforms and at different resolutions. Spatial
        transcriptomics preserves location; single-cell RNA-seq resolves cell identity and state.
        Integrating the two is critical when the biological question is how local cellular programs
        assemble into tissue phenotypes. I develop frameworks that combine NanoString GeoMx and
        CosMx with single-cell RNA-seq in rhesus macaque models of SIV and
        <em>Mycobacterium tuberculosis</em> infection, using deconvolution and spatial statistics
        to connect pathology to mechanism within the limits of each assay.
      </p>
      <p class="meta">
        10X Genomics · GeoMx/CosMx · deconvolution · spatial statistics
      </p>

      <h3>Bacterial stress response and antibiotic tolerance</h3>
      <p>
        Bacteria respond to divergent stresses through overlapping transcriptional programs, yet the
        path from a population-level stimulant to rare antibiotic-tolerant states remains difficult
        to predict. Using transcriptomic profiling and stochastic modeling, I studied how
        <em>E. coli</em> enters persister states under stress, with attention to shared stimulons
        and the rare-state dynamics that link molecular fluctuations to population-level tolerance.
        This work includes co-first authorship with Wang et al. (2023, 2021) and modeling with
        Gillespie simulations and agent-based approaches.
      </p>
      <p class="meta">Wang et al. (2023, 2021) — co-first author · Gillespie / ABM · time series</p>

      <h2>Approaches</h2>
      <p>
        The methods below are the practical inventory I use to move between molecular models,
        single-cell measurements, and tissue-scale organization. Tool development appears when
        existing pipelines cannot resolve the relationship under study (e.g., hashing, TCR
        clustering, or immune/viral gene spaces via RIRA-related work).
      </p>
      <h3>Transcriptomics &amp; spatial biology</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Single-cell RNA-seq (10X), cell hashing, demultiplexing</li>
        <li>Spatial platforms: GeoMx DSP and CosMx</li>
        <li>
          Tools: <a href="https://github.com/BimberLab/cellhashR">cellhashR</a>,
          <a href="https://github.com/GWMcElfresh/tcrClustR">tcrClustR</a>,
          <a href="https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2025.1596760">nimble</a> (immune/viral gene spaces)
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Mathematical &amp; computational modeling</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Stochastic biochemical models (Gillespie, CME)</li>
        <li>Agent-based models of cellular populations</li>
        <li>Multiscale links from molecule → cell → tissue</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Structural biology (earlier work)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Template-based protein docking (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/prot.25875">Chakravarty et al., 2020</a>)
        </li>
        <li>
          DNA–ligand vibrational entropy in AutoDock (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.compbiolchem.2018.03.027">McElfresh &amp; Deligkaris, 2018</a>)
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Philosophy</h2>
      <p>
        Disease phenotypes emerge from coupling across scales: molecular mechanisms within cells,
        heterogeneous states in a population, and spatial organization in tissue. Treating any one
        of these as a complete summary of the others obscures the transfer that often determines
        outcome. I therefore organize work around that transfer — asking what a measurement or
        model can distinguish, and what it necessarily leaves unresolved.
      </p>
      <p>
        Method development follows from that constraint. Pipelines should be reproducible and
        robust enough to support a biological comparison; they should not invent complexity that
        the question does not require. Computation is useful to the extent that it clarifies a
        disease mechanism or makes an experimental contrast interpretable. Much of this depends on
        collaboration with experimental immunology, which supplies the systems and controls that
        keep models accountable to biology.
      </p>

      <p>
        If a shared question depends on linking these scales, <a href={`mailto:${site.email}`}>reach out</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .section-label {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0;
  }

  .research-overview {
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }
</style>
